<DOC><DOCNO> AP880407-0211 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1830EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-07 0565</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0582</SECOND><HEAD>High Wind, Rain Along Mid-Atlantic Coast, Heat Wave in Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm packing powerful winds swept across the Atlantic Coaston Thursday, drenching an area from Maryland to New Jersey, whiletemperatures climbed to record levels in the northern Plains.   Rivers swelled to near flood stage in Indiana, Ohio andMichigan, where basements in Delta Township, in south-centralMichigan, were flooded after heavy rain Wednesday.   The storm produced a record wind gust of 172 mph Wednesday nighton Grandfather Mountain, in western North Carolina. Winds of 69 mphand gusts to 115 mph were recorded Thursday morning.   The mid-Atlantic states also had strong winds Thursday, with agust of 48 mph at Baltimore and 44 mph at Wrightstown, N.J. A gustof 46 mph was recorded at Atlanta.   Gale warnings were in effect for Atlantic coastal waters fromNew Jersey to Delaware and from South Carolina to northern Florida.   Rain was widespread Thurdsay afternoon across Maryland,Pennsylvania, Delaware and New Jersey.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 0.78 inch at Patuxent Naval Air Station, Md., 0.74 inch atSalisbury, Md., 0.65 inch at Dover, Del., 0.63 inch at Washington,D.C., 0.60 inch at Harrisburg, Pa., 0.56 inch at Millville, N.J.,and 0.53 inch at Philadelphia.   Flood warnings were posted along St. Joseph River in southernMichigan, northern Indiana and northwest Ohio. The river wasexpected to crest at up to 3 feet above flood stage during the nextcouple of days, causing flooding of lowlands and secondary roads.Similar flooding was expected along the Kankakee River in northwestIndiana.   Warm temperatures prevailed in the Plains, where readings werein the 70s and 80s in the Dakotas, eastern portions of Wyoming andColorado.   Temperatures reached record highs in Duluth, Minn., 66; Fargo,N.D.; 76; Minot, N.D., 80; Rapid City, S.D., 82; and Sioux City,Iowa, 85. Records were tied in Aberdeen, S.D., 85, and Scottsbluff,Neb., 82.   To the northwest, a cold front sent temperatures in westernMontana down to the lower 40s. A winter storm watch for possibleheavy snow was in effect overnight for the mountains ofsouth-central montana.   In the desert Southwest, temperatures were in the 80s and lower90s by midday, and a wind advisory was posted for the deserts ofsouthern California and southern Nevada.   A high-wind warning was in effect in extreme western Nevada,where a gust of 61 mph was recorded at Reno late Thursday morning.   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 37 degrees at Mullan,Idaho, to 92 degrees at Yuma, Ariz. The morning low was 21 degreesat Yellowstone Park, Wyo.   Friday's forecast called for rain from North Carolina across themid-Atlantic states to New England, showers and thunderstormsscattered from the Dakotas across the Nebraska Panhandle andsoutheast Wyoming to Colorado, rain and mountain snow in Wyoming,southeast Idaho and Utah, rain and snow showers in Montana, andscattered showers in southern Texas.   Highs temperatures were expected to climb into the 80s from thelower Mississippi Valley across the central and southern Plains tothe desert Southwest, into the 40s or 50s from North Carolina toNew England and across the central and northern Appalachians to theGreat Lakes, into the 40s and 50s from western portions of theDakotas to the Pacific Northwest and into the 60s or 70s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>